  <span id="freeText8605665844212319864" style="display:none">I read this book a few years ago and my reading experience was very much as you described it. Can’t really grasp what is implicit and double meanings through the many passages and meetings. My resolution with the book and author — as I get the same experience with his other titles <br />— is by acknowledging an existence of several gaps. Cultural, also accounting this idea that I have that both genders have difficulties of expressing thoughts and feelings, even nowadays I think it is a significant trait, enveloped by other psychological traits. Also cultural by the western contrast of daily routine, daily values, and the geisha culture and history by itself, that is different from the sex-worker definition that we hold nowadays. Time itself, since this is a title of the 30’s.<br /><br />I might be giving to much credit for how much I don’t know about all the mentioned topics, but that is also where I hold this author’s titles: a photographic portrait of certain Japan, at a place, at an hour, around these characters. And it is foreign and sometimes at levels that I call weird, and difficult to relate, as proof of a very different context. Even more difficult if we analyse it through the Present lens.<br /><br />Putting awards aside and focusing on the value of this title, I will say that this plays differently to western and eastern cultures. And for us westerns, might be the non-familiarity impressions of this photographic portrait that we got to know.</span>
